For an Airy stress function \(\phi(x,y) = C_1 x y + C_2 x y^3 + C_3 x^2 y^2 + C_4 x^3 y\), the plane-stress components are \(\sigma_x = \partial^2 \phi / \partial y^2\), \(\sigma_y = \partial^2 \phi / \partial x^2\), and \(	au_{xy} = -\partial^2 \phi / (\partial x \partial y)\). 1) Compute stresses: 
\(\sigma_x = 2 C_2 x y + 2 C_3 x^2 + 6 C_4 x^3\); 
\(\sigma_y = 2 C_3 y^2 + 6 C_4 x y\); 
\(	au_{xy} = -C_1 - 3 C_2 y^2 - 2 C_3 x y - 3 C_4 x^2\). 2) Top and bottom surfaces (\(y = \pm d\)) are traction-free, so both \(\sigma_y = 0\) and \(	au_{xy} = 0\) there for all \(x\). From \(\sigma_y = 2 C_3 d^2 + 6 C_4 x (\pm d)\) to vanish for all \(x\) and both signs of \(y\), we must have \(C_3 = 0\) and \(C_4 = 0\). Then \(\sigma_y \equiv 0\). With \(C_3 = C_4 = 0\), \(	au_{xy} = -C_1 - 3 C_2 y^2\). Traction-free top and bottom require \(	au_{xy}(y = \pm d) = 0\), giving \(-C_1 - 3 C_2 d^2 = 0\) or \(C_1 = -3 C_2 d^2\). 3) At the right edge (say \(x = L\)), the only non-zero traction is shear, with given parabolic distribution \(	au_{xy} = -\lambda [1 - (y/d)^2]\). Our expression is independent of \(x\), so it must match this for all \(y\): \(-C_1 - 3 C_2 y^2 = -\lambda + (\lambda/d^2) y^2\). Equating coefficients of \(y^0\) and \(y^2\) gives \(-C_1 = -\lambda \Rightarrow C_1 = \lambda\) and \(-3 C_2 = \lambda/d^2 \Rightarrow C_2 = -\lambda/(3 d^2)\). This also satisfies \(C_1 = -3 C_2 d^2\). Thus the admissible constants are \(C_1 = \lambda, C_2 = -\lambda/(3 d^2), C_3 = 0, C_4 = 0\), which corresponds to option D. The proposed polynomial Airy function is biharmonic by construction (all terms are of degree 2 or 4 in x,y), so with these constants it satisfies both the biharmonic equation and all boundary conditions.
